[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":1110},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F13\u002Flearn-python-from-javascript-12-operators\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F13\u002Flearn-python-from-javascript-12-operators\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F13\u002Flearn-python-from-javascript-12-operators\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F13\u002Flearn-python-from-javascript-12-operators\u002F":1088,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F13\u002Flearn-python-from-javascript-12-operators\u002F":1097},"\u002Fpython\u002F20210913\u002F3862334805\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":1071,"date":1072,"description":1073,"extension":1074,"lang":1075,"meta":1076,"navigation":802,"path":1077,"readingMinutes":492,"seo":1078,"standalone":1079,"stem":1080,"tags":1081,"tldr":1085,"updated":1072,"url":1086,"__hash__":1087},"content\u002Fen\u002FPython\u002Flearn-python-from-javascript-12-operators.md","Learn Python From a JavaScript Angle (12) - Operators","1002415298",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":1059},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,44,47,157,160,187,190,193,200,203,206,210,213,228,231,234,248,251,257,272,275,289,300,303,306,312,317,324,333,339,354,357,377,380,400,406,421,425,428,435,525,528,608,611,686,694,701,726,729,739,768,771,780,783,814,817,832,851,855,863,874,877,892,899,902,911,917,920,926,933,936,941,962,971,978,981,985,1006,1010,1013,1017,1049,1055],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"Operators are something you reach for constantly, so there's no way to skip them in the basics.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"operators","Operators",[17,25,26,27,31,32,35,36,39,40,43],{},"The most basic operators are the usual suspects: ",[28,29,30],"code",{},"+"," (add), ",[28,33,34],{},"-"," (subtract), ",[28,37,38],{},"*"," (multiply), ",[28,41,42],{},"\u002F"," (divide). These are called arithmetic operators, and the way you write them in JavaScript isn't much different from Python.",[17,45,46],{},"JavaScript:",[48,49,54],"pre",{"className":50,"code":51,"language":52,"meta":53,"style":53},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","console.log(1 + 1); \u002F\u002F 2\nconsole.log(2 * 2); \u002F\u002F 4\nconsole.log(8 - 2); \u002F\u002F 6\nconsole.log(16 \u002F 2); \u002F\u002F 8\n","js","",[28,55,56,90,113,135],{"__ignoreMap":53},[57,58,61,65,69,72,76,80,83,86],"span",{"class":59,"line":60},"line",1,[57,62,64],{"class":63},"sMAXC","console.",[57,66,68],{"class":67},"sj_SG","log",[57,70,71],{"class":63},"(",[57,73,75],{"class":74},"sCcAr","1",[57,77,79],{"class":78},"sWyjQ"," +",[57,81,82],{"class":74}," 1",[57,84,85],{"class":63},"); ",[57,87,89],{"class":88},"sQrFR","\u002F\u002F 2\n",[57,91,93,95,97,99,102,105,108,110],{"class":59,"line":92},2,[57,94,64],{"class":63},[57,96,68],{"class":67},[57,98,71],{"class":63},[57,100,101],{"class":74},"2",[57,103,104],{"class":78}," *",[57,106,107],{"class":74}," 2",[57,109,85],{"class":63},[57,111,112],{"class":88},"\u002F\u002F 4\n",[57,114,116,118,120,122,125,128,130,132],{"class":59,"line":115},3,[57,117,64],{"class":63},[57,119,68],{"class":67},[57,121,71],{"class":63},[57,123,124],{"class":74},"8",[57,126,127],{"class":78}," -",[57,129,107],{"class":74},[57,131,85],{"class":63},[57,133,134],{"class":88},"\u002F\u002F 6\n",[57,136,138,140,142,144,147,150,152,154],{"class":59,"line":137},4,[57,139,64],{"class":63},[57,141,68],{"class":67},[57,143,71],{"class":63},[57,145,146],{"class":74},"16",[57,148,149],{"class":78}," \u002F",[57,151,107],{"class":74},[57,153,85],{"class":63},[57,155,156],{"class":88},"\u002F\u002F 8\n",[17,158,159],{},"Python:",[48,161,165],{"className":162,"code":163,"language":164,"meta":53,"style":53},"language-py shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","print(1 + 1) # 2\nprint(2 * 2) # 4\nprint(8 - 2) # 6\nprint(16 \u002F 2) # 8.0\n","py",[28,166,167,172,177,182],{"__ignoreMap":53},[57,168,169],{"class":59,"line":60},[57,170,171],{},"print(1 + 1) # 2\n",[57,173,174],{"class":59,"line":92},[57,175,176],{},"print(2 * 2) # 4\n",[57,178,179],{"class":59,"line":115},[57,180,181],{},"print(8 - 2) # 6\n",[57,183,184],{"class":59,"line":137},[57,185,186],{},"print(16 \u002F 2) # 8.0\n",[17,188,189],{},"The four basic operations look almost identical, except for division. Notice that Python outputs a float there.",[17,191,192],{},"Wait, did you catch that? Python's division spits out a float.",[17,194,195],{},[196,197],"img",{"alt":198,"src":199},"Wait what...","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FPython\u002F%E5%BE%9E%20JavaScript%20%E8%A7%92%E5%BA%A6%E5%AD%B8%20Python\u002F1631017732503.png",[17,201,202],{},"If you've ever written Python 2, you might be even more confused.",[17,204,205],{},"So let me drop in a quick aside about the difference between Python 2 and Python 3.",[12,207,209],{"id":208},"python-2-vs-python-3-division-operator","Python 2 vs Python 3 Division Operator",[17,211,212],{},"This is one of those quirky spots. In the original Python 2, division gives you an integer:",[48,214,216],{"className":162,"code":215,"language":164,"meta":53,"style":53},"# Python2\nprint(16 \u002F 2) # 8\n",[28,217,218,223],{"__ignoreMap":53},[57,219,220],{"class":59,"line":60},[57,221,222],{},"# Python2\n",[57,224,225],{"class":59,"line":92},[57,226,227],{},"print(16 \u002F 2) # 8\n",[17,229,230],{},"It doesn't look like a big deal at first, but if you're building a system that needs precision, it actually causes problems. Python 2's division floors the decimal, which is why it's also called floor division or integer division.",[17,232,233],{},"So, like I said, if we want more precise handling, things get a little weird:",[48,235,237],{"className":162,"code":236,"language":164,"meta":53,"style":53},"# Python2\nprint(16 \u002F 3 == 16.0 \u002F 3.0) # False\n",[28,238,239,243],{"__ignoreMap":53},[57,240,241],{"class":59,"line":60},[57,242,222],{},[57,244,245],{"class":59,"line":92},[57,246,247],{},"print(16 \u002F 3 == 16.0 \u002F 3.0) # False\n",[17,249,250],{},"Surprised? If you're not, I sure was, because these two should be equal. The reason is that Python 2's division operator actually has two abilities, both floating point division and integer division. The moment you tack a decimal point onto a number, it gets converted to floating point division.",[17,252,253,254,256],{},"To fix this, Python 3 onwards stripped the ",[28,255,42],{}," operator down to just floating point division. So in Python 3 the result becomes:",[48,258,260],{"className":162,"code":259,"language":164,"meta":53,"style":53},"# Python3\nprint(16 \u002F 3) # 5.333333333333333\n",[28,261,262,267],{"__ignoreMap":53},[57,263,264],{"class":59,"line":60},[57,265,266],{},"# Python3\n",[57,268,269],{"class":59,"line":92},[57,270,271],{},"print(16 \u002F 3) # 5.333333333333333\n",[17,273,274],{},"And thanks to that fix, our precise calculations are a lot safer:",[48,276,278],{"className":162,"code":277,"language":164,"meta":53,"style":53},"# Python3\nprint(16 \u002F 3 == 16.0 \u002F 3.0) # True\n",[28,279,280,284],{"__ignoreMap":53},[57,281,282],{"class":59,"line":60},[57,283,266],{},[57,285,286],{"class":59,"line":92},[57,287,288],{},"print(16 \u002F 3 == 16.0 \u002F 3.0) # True\n",[17,290,291,292,299],{},"If you want to dig deeper, I'd recommend reading the official \"",[293,294,298],"a",{"href":295,"rel":296},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.python.org\u002Fdev\u002Fpeps\u002Fpep-0238\u002F",[297],"nofollow","PEP 238 -- Changing the Division Operator","\" document.",[17,301,302],{},"Okay, at this point you're probably thinking, \"What if I actually want integer division?\"",[17,304,305],{},"So let's keep going.",[17,307,308],{},[196,309],{"alt":310,"src":311},"Let's keep going","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FPython\u002F%E5%BE%9E%20JavaScript%20%E8%A7%92%E5%BA%A6%E5%AD%B8%20Python\u002F9446703ab8eced2faa7f9505e5c1ed15.png",[313,314,316],"h3",{"id":315},"operator","\u002F\u002F operator",[17,318,319,320,323],{},"Because of Python 3's fix, if you still want integer division, you can use the ",[28,321,322],{},"\u002F\u002F"," operator:",[48,325,327],{"className":162,"code":326,"language":164,"meta":53,"style":53},"print(16 \u002F\u002F 3) # 5\n",[28,328,329],{"__ignoreMap":53},[57,330,331],{"class":59,"line":60},[57,332,326],{},[17,334,335,336,338],{},"The ",[28,337,322],{}," operator gives you the integer division behavior that Python 2 used to have:",[48,340,342],{"className":162,"code":341,"language":164,"meta":53,"style":53},"print(16 \u002F\u002F 2) # 8\nprint(type(16 \u002F\u002F 2)) # int\n",[28,343,344,349],{"__ignoreMap":53},[57,345,346],{"class":59,"line":60},[57,347,348],{},"print(16 \u002F\u002F 2) # 8\n",[57,350,351],{"class":59,"line":92},[57,352,353],{},"print(type(16 \u002F\u002F 2)) # int\n",[17,355,356],{},"But here's where it gets tricky. Try to guess what the following code outputs:",[48,358,360],{"className":162,"code":359,"language":164,"meta":53,"style":53},"print(100 \u002F 3, type(100 \u002F 3)) # ?, ?\nprint(100 \u002F\u002F 3, type(100 \u002F\u002F 3)) # ?, ?\nprint(100. \u002F\u002F 3, type(100. \u002F\u002F 3)) # ?, ?\n",[28,361,362,367,372],{"__ignoreMap":53},[57,363,364],{"class":59,"line":60},[57,365,366],{},"print(100 \u002F 3, type(100 \u002F 3)) # ?, ?\n",[57,368,369],{"class":59,"line":92},[57,370,371],{},"print(100 \u002F\u002F 3, type(100 \u002F\u002F 3)) # ?, ?\n",[57,373,374],{"class":59,"line":115},[57,375,376],{},"print(100. \u002F\u002F 3, type(100. \u002F\u002F 3)) # ?, ?\n",[17,378,379],{},"Nervous yet? Let's see the results:",[48,381,383],{"className":162,"code":382,"language":164,"meta":53,"style":53},"print(100 \u002F 3, type(100 \u002F 3)) # 33.333333333333336, float\nprint(100 \u002F\u002F 3, type(100 \u002F\u002F 3)) # 33, int\nprint(100. \u002F\u002F 3, type(100. \u002F\u002F 3)) # 33.0, float\n",[28,384,385,390,395],{"__ignoreMap":53},[57,386,387],{"class":59,"line":60},[57,388,389],{},"print(100 \u002F 3, type(100 \u002F 3)) # 33.333333333333336, float\n",[57,391,392],{"class":59,"line":92},[57,393,394],{},"print(100 \u002F\u002F 3, type(100 \u002F\u002F 3)) # 33, int\n",[57,396,397],{"class":59,"line":115},[57,398,399],{},"print(100. \u002F\u002F 3, type(100. \u002F\u002F 3)) # 33.0, float\n",[17,401,402],{},[196,403],{"alt":404,"src":405},"Arrow to the knee","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FPython\u002F%E5%BE%9E%20JavaScript%20%E8%A7%92%E5%BA%A6%E5%AD%B8%20Python\u002F1629620892000.png",[17,407,408,409,411,412,416,417,420],{},"In short, ",[28,410,322],{}," has the same ability as Python 2 did, carrying both ",[413,414,415],"strong",{},"integer division"," and ",[413,418,419],{},"floating point division",", so you've got to be a bit careful when you use it.",[12,422,424],{"id":423},"merging-lists","Merging Lists",[17,426,427],{},"Let me also mention the plus operator here, because it's actually pretty special.",[17,429,430,431,434],{},"Why do I say that? Well, for example, if you want to merge two arrays in JavaScript, the simplest way is the ",[28,432,433],{},"concat()"," function:",[48,436,438],{"className":50,"code":437,"language":52,"meta":53,"style":53},"var a = [1, 2, 3];\nvar b = [4, 5, 6];\nvar c = a.concat(b);\nconsole.log(c); \u002F\u002F [ 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6 ]\n",[28,439,440,469,495,513],{"__ignoreMap":53},[57,441,442,445,448,451,454,456,459,461,463,466],{"class":59,"line":60},[57,443,444],{"class":78},"var",[57,446,447],{"class":63}," a ",[57,449,450],{"class":78},"=",[57,452,453],{"class":63}," [",[57,455,75],{"class":74},[57,457,458],{"class":63},", ",[57,460,101],{"class":74},[57,462,458],{"class":63},[57,464,465],{"class":74},"3",[57,467,468],{"class":63},"];\n",[57,470,471,473,476,478,480,483,485,488,490,493],{"class":59,"line":92},[57,472,444],{"class":78},[57,474,475],{"class":63}," b ",[57,477,450],{"class":78},[57,479,453],{"class":63},[57,481,482],{"class":74},"4",[57,484,458],{"class":63},[57,486,487],{"class":74},"5",[57,489,458],{"class":63},[57,491,492],{"class":74},"6",[57,494,468],{"class":63},[57,496,497,499,502,504,507,510],{"class":59,"line":115},[57,498,444],{"class":78},[57,500,501],{"class":63}," c ",[57,503,450],{"class":78},[57,505,506],{"class":63}," a.",[57,508,509],{"class":67},"concat",[57,511,512],{"class":63},"(b);\n",[57,514,515,517,519,522],{"class":59,"line":137},[57,516,64],{"class":63},[57,518,68],{"class":67},[57,520,521],{"class":63},"(c); ",[57,523,524],{"class":88},"\u002F\u002F [ 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6 ]\n",[17,526,527],{},"A slightly more advanced approach is to use the ES6 spread operator:",[48,529,531],{"className":50,"code":530,"language":52,"meta":53,"style":53},"var a = [1, 2, 3];\nvar b = [4, 5, 6];\nvar c = [...a, ...b];\nconsole.log(c); \u002F\u002F [ 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6 ]\n",[28,532,533,555,577,598],{"__ignoreMap":53},[57,534,535,537,539,541,543,545,547,549,551,553],{"class":59,"line":60},[57,536,444],{"class":78},[57,538,447],{"class":63},[57,540,450],{"class":78},[57,542,453],{"class":63},[57,544,75],{"class":74},[57,546,458],{"class":63},[57,548,101],{"class":74},[57,550,458],{"class":63},[57,552,465],{"class":74},[57,554,468],{"class":63},[57,556,557,559,561,563,565,567,569,571,573,575],{"class":59,"line":92},[57,558,444],{"class":78},[57,560,475],{"class":63},[57,562,450],{"class":78},[57,564,453],{"class":63},[57,566,482],{"class":74},[57,568,458],{"class":63},[57,570,487],{"class":74},[57,572,458],{"class":63},[57,574,492],{"class":74},[57,576,468],{"class":63},[57,578,579,581,583,585,587,590,593,595],{"class":59,"line":115},[57,580,444],{"class":78},[57,582,501],{"class":63},[57,584,450],{"class":78},[57,586,453],{"class":63},[57,588,589],{"class":78},"...",[57,591,592],{"class":63},"a, ",[57,594,589],{"class":78},[57,596,597],{"class":63},"b];\n",[57,599,600,602,604,606],{"class":59,"line":137},[57,601,64],{"class":63},[57,603,68],{"class":67},[57,605,521],{"class":63},[57,607,524],{"class":88},[17,609,610],{},"But if you use the plus operator, you get something completely different:",[48,612,614],{"className":50,"code":613,"language":52,"meta":53,"style":53},"var a = [1, 2, 3];\nvar b = [4, 5, 6];\nvar c = a + b;\nconsole.log(c); \u002F\u002F \"1,2,34,5,6\"\n",[28,615,616,638,660,675],{"__ignoreMap":53},[57,617,618,620,622,624,626,628,630,632,634,636],{"class":59,"line":60},[57,619,444],{"class":78},[57,621,447],{"class":63},[57,623,450],{"class":78},[57,625,453],{"class":63},[57,627,75],{"class":74},[57,629,458],{"class":63},[57,631,101],{"class":74},[57,633,458],{"class":63},[57,635,465],{"class":74},[57,637,468],{"class":63},[57,639,640,642,644,646,648,650,652,654,656,658],{"class":59,"line":92},[57,641,444],{"class":78},[57,643,475],{"class":63},[57,645,450],{"class":78},[57,647,453],{"class":63},[57,649,482],{"class":74},[57,651,458],{"class":63},[57,653,487],{"class":74},[57,655,458],{"class":63},[57,657,492],{"class":74},[57,659,468],{"class":63},[57,661,662,664,666,668,670,672],{"class":59,"line":115},[57,663,444],{"class":78},[57,665,501],{"class":63},[57,667,450],{"class":78},[57,669,447],{"class":63},[57,671,30],{"class":78},[57,673,674],{"class":63}," b;\n",[57,676,677,679,681,683],{"class":59,"line":137},[57,678,64],{"class":63},[57,680,68],{"class":67},[57,682,521],{"class":63},[57,684,685],{"class":88},"\u002F\u002F \"1,2,34,5,6\"\n",[17,687,688,689,693],{},"As for why, you can check out the ",[293,690,692],{"href":691},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20200628\u002F4021116713\u002F","notes"," (article in Mandarin) I wrote earlier where I covered this concept, so I won't repeat it here.",[17,695,696,697,700],{},"So what about Python? Python is a bit more special. You can use the ",[413,698,699],{},"plus operator"," to merge arrays quickly:",[48,702,704],{"className":162,"code":703,"language":164,"meta":53,"style":53},"a = [1, 2 ,3]\nb = [4, 5, 6]\nc = a + b\nprint(c) # [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]\n",[28,705,706,711,716,721],{"__ignoreMap":53},[57,707,708],{"class":59,"line":60},[57,709,710],{},"a = [1, 2 ,3]\n",[57,712,713],{"class":59,"line":92},[57,714,715],{},"b = [4, 5, 6]\n",[57,717,718],{"class":59,"line":115},[57,719,720],{},"c = a + b\n",[57,722,723],{"class":59,"line":137},[57,724,725],{},"print(c) # [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]\n",[17,727,728],{},"Super simple, right?",[17,730,731,732,735,736,738],{},"Let me also quickly mention another way to merge arrays, the ",[28,733,734],{},"extend()"," from the previous chapter. But watch out: ",[28,737,734],{}," modifies the original array, so it won't return the result into a new variable. Keep that in mind:",[48,740,742],{"className":162,"code":741,"language":164,"meta":53,"style":53},"a = [1, 2 ,3]\nb = [4, 5, 6]\nc = a.extend(b)\nprint(c) # None\nprint(a) # [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]\n",[28,743,744,748,752,757,762],{"__ignoreMap":53},[57,745,746],{"class":59,"line":60},[57,747,710],{},[57,749,750],{"class":59,"line":92},[57,751,715],{},[57,753,754],{"class":59,"line":115},[57,755,756],{},"c = a.extend(b)\n",[57,758,759],{"class":59,"line":137},[57,760,761],{},"print(c) # None\n",[57,763,765],{"class":59,"line":764},5,[57,766,767],{},"print(a) # [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]\n",[17,769,770],{},"Oh, and one more thing. Python has some fun tricks too. For example, you can use the multiplication operator to repeat a string:",[48,772,774],{"className":162,"code":773,"language":164,"meta":53,"style":53},"print('Ray' * 4) # RayRayRayRay\n",[28,775,776],{"__ignoreMap":53},[57,777,778],{"class":59,"line":60},[57,779,773],{},[17,781,782],{},"You can even repeat lists and tuples:",[48,784,786],{"className":162,"code":785,"language":164,"meta":53,"style":53},"# tuple\nprint(('https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002Fisraynotarray', '\u002F') * 4) # ('https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002Fisraynotarray', '\u002F', 'https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002Fisraynotarray', '\u002F', 'https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002Fisraynotarray', '\u002F', 'https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002Fisraynotarray', '\u002F')\n\n# list\nprint(['https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002Fisraynotarray', '\u002F'] * 4) # ['https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002Fisraynotarray', '\u002F', 'https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002Fisraynotarray', '\u002F', 'https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002Fisraynotarray', '\u002F', 'https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002Fisraynotarray', '\u002F']\n",[28,787,788,793,798,804,809],{"__ignoreMap":53},[57,789,790],{"class":59,"line":60},[57,791,792],{},"# tuple\n",[57,794,795],{"class":59,"line":92},[57,796,797],{},"print(('https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002Fisraynotarray', '\u002F') * 4) # ('https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002Fisraynotarray', '\u002F', 'https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002Fisraynotarray', '\u002F', 'https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002Fisraynotarray', '\u002F', 'https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002Fisraynotarray', '\u002F')\n",[57,799,800],{"class":59,"line":115},[57,801,803],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":802},true,"\n",[57,805,806],{"class":59,"line":137},[57,807,808],{},"# list\n",[57,810,811],{"class":59,"line":764},[57,812,813],{},"print(['https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002Fisraynotarray', '\u002F'] * 4) # ['https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002Fisraynotarray', '\u002F', 'https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002Fisraynotarray', '\u002F', 'https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002Fisraynotarray', '\u002F', 'https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002Fisraynotarray', '\u002F']\n",[17,815,816],{},"And within the four basic operations, there are some more advanced uses too, like exponentiation:",[48,818,820],{"className":162,"code":819,"language":164,"meta":53,"style":53},"print(10 ** 2) # 100\nprint(12 ** 2) # 144\n",[28,821,822,827],{"__ignoreMap":53},[57,823,824],{"class":59,"line":60},[57,825,826],{},"print(10 ** 2) # 100\n",[57,828,829],{"class":59,"line":92},[57,830,831],{},"print(12 ** 2) # 144\n",[17,833,834,835,838,839,842,843,846,847,850],{},"There are other common operators too, like greater than (",[28,836,837],{},">","), less than (",[28,840,841],{},"\u003C","), greater than or equal (",[28,844,845],{},">=","), less than or equal (",[28,848,849],{},"\u003C=","), and so on. I'm just listing out the extra arithmetic bits here.",[12,852,854],{"id":853},"operator-precedence-and-associativity","Operator Precedence and Associativity",[17,856,857,858,862],{},"Lastly, I want to talk about a question that comes up a lot in JavaScript interviews. In JavaScript we know there's the concept of precedence and associativity. If you're not clear on it, I'd recommend the article ",[293,859,861],{"href":860},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20200628\u002F713590185\u002F","JavaScript Core Concepts (16) - Operators, Types and Grammar - Precedence and Associativity"," (article in Mandarin).",[17,864,865,866,869,870,873],{},"A classic JavaScript example is ",[28,867,868],{},"console.log(1 \u003C 2 \u003C 3); \u002F\u002F true",", but flip it to ",[28,871,872],{},"console.log(3 > 2 > 1); \u002F\u002F false"," and the result changes.",[17,875,876],{},"So I wanted to explore whether Python has this problem too. Let's actually try it:",[48,878,880],{"className":162,"code":879,"language":164,"meta":53,"style":53},"print(1 \u003C 2 \u003C 3) # True\nprint(3 > 2 > 1) # True\n",[28,881,882,887],{"__ignoreMap":53},[57,883,884],{"class":59,"line":60},[57,885,886],{},"print(1 \u003C 2 \u003C 3) # True\n",[57,888,889],{"class":59,"line":92},[57,890,891],{},"print(3 > 2 > 1) # True\n",[17,893,894,895,898],{},"You can see both results are ",[28,896,897],{},"True",". Does that mean Python doesn't have the precedence and associativity problem?",[17,900,901],{},"It actually does.",[17,903,904,905,910],{},"In the ",[293,906,909],{"href":907,"rel":908},"https:\u002F\u002Fdocs.python.org\u002F3\u002Freference\u002Fexpressions.html#operator-precedence",[297],"Python docs"," there's this line:",[912,913,914],"blockquote",{},[17,915,916],{},"Note that comparisons, membership tests, and identity tests, all have the same precedence and have a left-to-right chaining feature as described in the Comparisons section.",[17,918,919],{},"So in that link you can also see the table below, where the top has the highest precedence and the bottom has the lowest:",[17,921,922],{},[196,923],{"alt":924,"src":925},"Operator precedence","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FPython\u002F%E5%BE%9E%20JavaScript%20%E8%A7%92%E5%BA%A6%E5%AD%B8%20Python\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202021-07-11%2022.20.06.png",[17,927,928,929,932],{},"So how does the earlier example ",[28,930,931],{},"print(3 > 2 > 1) # True"," actually work?",[17,934,935],{},"We can figure it out from the official explanation:",[912,937,938],{},[17,939,940],{},"For example, x \u003C y \u003C= z is equivalent to x \u003C y and y \u003C= z, except that y is evaluated only once (but in both cases z is not evaluated at all when x \u003C y is found to be false).",[17,942,943,944,416,947,950,951,954,955,958,959,961],{},"From that explanation, we can tell the example code actually runs as ",[28,945,946],{},"3 > 2",[28,948,949],{},"2 > 1",". Note that the middle is an ",[28,952,953],{},"and",", meaning if either side is ",[28,956,957],{},"False",", the whole thing returns ",[28,960,957],{},". For example:",[48,963,965],{"className":162,"code":964,"language":164,"meta":53,"style":53},"print(3 > 2 > 4) # False\n",[28,966,967],{"__ignoreMap":53},[57,968,969],{"class":59,"line":60},[57,970,964],{},[17,972,973,974,977],{},"To put it more plainly, the result is like ",[28,975,976],{},"3 > 2 and 2 > 4",".",[17,979,980],{},"And that's it for our operators chapter.",[12,982,984],{"id":983},"references","References",[986,987,988,996,1001],"ul",{},[989,990,991],"li",{},[293,992,995],{"href":993,"rel":994},"https:\u002F\u002Fdocs.python.org\u002F3\u002Freference\u002Fexpressions.html#comparisons",[297],"Comparisons",[989,997,998],{},[293,999,924],{"href":907,"rel":1000},[297],[989,1002,1003],{},[293,1004,298],{"href":295,"rel":1005},[297],[12,1007,1009],{"id":1008},"authors-note","Author's Note",[17,1011,1012],{},"I found an article titled \"The Soft-Boiled Egg Recipe That Never Fails,\" and after trying it... I still failed, lol. I'm just way too out of practice. That said, I have to admit the fishy smell of organic eggs really isn't that bad.",[12,1014,1016],{"id":1015},"about-the-rabbits","About the Rabbits",[986,1018,1019,1026,1034,1042],{},[989,1020,1021],{},[293,1022,1025],{"href":1023,"rel":1024},"https:\u002F\u002Ftailwindcss.tw",[297],"Tailwind CSS Taiwan Official Site",[989,1027,1028,1033],{},[293,1029,1032],{"href":1030,"rel":1031},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002Ftailwindcss.tw",[297],"Tailwind CSS Taiwan"," (Facebook fan page)",[989,1035,1036,1041],{},[293,1037,1040],{"href":1038,"rel":1039},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002Fgroups\u002Ftailwindcss.taiwan",[297],"Rabbit Cult x Tailwind CSS Taiwan"," (Facebook group)",[989,1043,1044],{},[293,1045,1048],{"href":1046,"rel":1047},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002Flalarabbits-%E5%85%94%E5%85%94%E6%95%99%E5%A4%A7%E6%9C%AC%E7%87%9F-102150975410839\u002F",[297],"Rabbit Cult HQ",[17,1050,1051],{},[196,1052],{"alt":1053,"src":1054},"The boundless power of the rabbit dharma","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FPwE2UE9.jpg",[1056,1057,1058],"style",{},"html pre.shiki code .sMAXC, html code.shiki .sMAXC{--shiki-default:#F0F3F6}html pre.shiki code .sj_SG, html code.shiki .sj_SG{--shiki-default:#DBB7FF}html pre.shiki code .sCcAr, html code.shiki .sCcAr{--shiki-default:#91CBFF}html pre.shiki code .sWyjQ, html code.shiki .sWyjQ{--shiki-default:#FF9492}html pre.shiki code .sQrFR, html code.shiki .sQrFR{--shiki-default:#BDC4CC}html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}",{"title":53,"searchDepth":92,"depth":92,"links":1060},[1061,1062,1063,1066,1067,1068,1069,1070],{"id":14,"depth":92,"text":15},{"id":22,"depth":92,"text":23},{"id":208,"depth":92,"text":209,"children":1064},[1065],{"id":315,"depth":115,"text":316},{"id":423,"depth":92,"text":424},{"id":853,"depth":92,"text":854},{"id":983,"depth":92,"text":984},{"id":1008,"depth":92,"text":1009},{"id":1015,"depth":92,"text":1016},"Python","2021-09-13 00:00:10","Operators are something you use constantly, so there's no skipping them in the basics. We'll look at the arithmetic operators, the surprising Python 2 vs Python 3 division difference, the floor division operator, merging lists with +, and the operator precedence gotcha that shows up in JavaScript interviews.","md","en",{},"\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002Flearn-python-from-javascript-12-operators",{"title":6,"description":1073},false,"en\u002FPython\u002Flearn-python-from-javascript-12-operators",[1071,1082,1083,1084],"JavaScript","Learn Python From a JavaScript Angle","13th iThome Ironman Contest",null,"\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F13\u002Flearn-python-from-javascript-12-operators\u002F","ki_Sy2JdS4DZ6BNrrS49eYsGyJ45LcO5XHhGjB86oKU",{"newer":1089,"older":1093},{"url":1090,"title":1091,"date":1092},"\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F14\u002Fpython-from-js-perspective-13-input-output\u002F","Learning Python From a JavaScript Angle (13): Reading Input and Printing Output","2021-09-14 00:00:10",{"url":1094,"title":1095,"date":1096},"\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F12\u002Flearning-python-from-javascript-11-list-20-operations\u002F","Learning Python From a JS Dev's View (11): 20 Ways to Work With Lists","2021-09-12 00:00:10",[1098,1102,1106],{"url":1099,"title":1100,"date":1101,"readingMinutes":482},"\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F10\u002F02\u002Flearn-python-from-javascript-31-finale\u002F","Learning Python from a JavaScript Angle (31): So What Do You Want to Learn Next?","2021-10-02 00:00:05",{"url":1103,"title":1104,"date":1105,"readingMinutes":492},"\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F10\u002F01\u002Flearning-python-from-javascript-30-web-scraping\u002F","Learning Python From JavaScript (30): Building a Web Scraper","2021-10-01 00:00:10",{"url":1107,"title":1108,"date":1109,"readingMinutes":492},"\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F30\u002Fpython-29-beautifulsoup\u002F","Learning Python From a JavaScript Angle (29) - BeautifulSoup","2021-09-30 00:00:10",1784011710005]